<paper id="1832719378"><title>Bitslice Ciphers and Power Analysis Attacks</title><year>2000</year><authors><author org="Proton World Intl." id="2022183134">Joan Daemen</author><author org="Proton World Intl." id="2164522652">Michael Peeters</author><author org="Proton World Intl." id="1974686051">Gilles Van Assche</author></authors><n_citation>26</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>134961700</reference><reference>169103730</reference><reference>1492619099</reference><reference>1546907539</reference><reference>1548656471</reference><reference>1573944628</reference><reference>1629301835</reference><reference>1765803531</reference><reference>1897761346</reference><reference>1964723977</reference><reference>1991897749</reference></references><venue id="2758283624" type="C">Fast Software Encryption</venue><doi>10.1007/3-540-44706-7_10</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.55912">Block size</keyword><keyword weight="0.44005">Power analysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.49345">BaseKing</keyword><keyword weight="0.42048">Secret sharing</keyword><keyword weight="0.50025">Block cipher</keyword><keyword weight="0.48492">Cryptography</keyword><keyword weight="0.40347">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.51494">Cryptanalysis</keyword><keyword weight="0.40516">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.56983">Linear cryptanalysis</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper, we present techniques to protect bitslice block ciphers against power analysis attacks. We analyze and extend a technique proposed in [12]. We apply the technique to BaseKing, a variant of 3-Way [9] that was published in [7]. We introduce an alternative method to protect against power analysis specific for BaseKing. Finally, we discuss the applicability of the methods to the other known bitslice ciphers 3-Way and Serpent [1].</abstract></paper>